# RLMAgents → rig-rlm: Ideas Worth Adopting

Analysis of [rlmagents](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents) (Python/LangChain fork) for ideas to bring into [rig-rlm](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm) (Rust/Rig monadic agent).

> [!NOTE]
> You already have a great [AGENTICA_IDEAS.md](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm/AGENTICA_IDEAS.md) from the Agentica analysis. This document focuses on **new** ideas from [rlmagents](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents) that go beyond what Agentica covered.

---

## What rlmagents Brings (that rig-rlm doesn't have yet)

### rig-rlm Already Has (✅ No Action Needed)

| Feature | rig-rlm location | Notes |
|---------|-------------------|-------|
| Monadic agent loop | `monad/` (14 files) | More mature than rlmagents' LangGraph graph |
| Sub-agent delegation | [pipeline.rs](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm/src/pipeline.rs) with [SubAgentConfig](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm/src/pipeline.rs#26-38) | Chunked parallel delegation |
| Capability-based permissions | [capabilities.rs](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm/src/monad/capabilities.rs) | [root](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm/src/monad/capabilities.rs#38-49), [code_worker](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm/src/monad/capabilities.rs#50-64), [analyst](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm/src/monad/capabilities.rs#65-79), [inference_only](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm/src/monad/capabilities.rs#80-91) |
| Safety guardrails | [safety.rs](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm/src/safety.rs) | Code validation, output sanitization, timeout wrapping |
| DSPy-rs prompt optimization | [agent_module.rs](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm/src/agent_module.rs) + GEPA | Unique to rig-rlm — rlmagents has nothing like this |
| Turso persistence | [persistence.rs](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm/src/persistence.rs) | Sessions + turns with full history |
| Sub-LLM bridging | [session.rs](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm/src/session.rs) with `llm_query()` | In-sandbox recursive calls |
| ARC benchmarks | [arc/](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/middleware/_tools.py#1018-1098) module | Evaluation infrastructure |

---

## 🔴 High-Impact Ideas

### 1. Multi-Context Isolation (RLM Contexts)

**What rlmagents does:**
Each analysis task gets one or more *isolated contexts* — named sandboxed workspaces with their own text buffer, REPL state, evidence, and variables. The agent can have `"config"`, `"source"`, `"logs"` contexts simultaneously, cross-reference between them, and they never pollute the main conversation history.

```
Key tools: load_context, load_file_context, peek_context, search_context,
           semantic_search, chunk_context, diff_contexts, cross_context_search
```

The [RLMSessionManager](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/session_manager.py#113-547) manages these contexts:
- Each context has its own REPL session with 100+ pre-loaded helpers
- Contexts track metadata: format, size, line count, token estimate
- Contexts can be serialized/deserialized ([save_session](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/session_manager.py#427-440)/[load_session](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/middleware/_tools.py#557-569))

**What rig-rlm lacks:**
[AgentContext](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm/src/monad/context.rs#129-153) has a single flat `HashMap<String, String>` for variables. There's no concept of named isolated workspaces for parallel data analysis.

**Adoption plan:**
```rust
struct IsolatedContext {
    id: String,
    content: String,
    metadata: ContextMetadata,  // format, size, tokens
    evidence: Vec<Evidence>,
    variables: HashMap<String, String>,
}

struct ContextManager {
    contexts: HashMap<String, IsolatedContext>,
}

impl ContextManager {
    fn load(&mut self, id: &str, content: &str) -> ContextMetadata;
    fn search(&self, id: &str, pattern: &str) -> Vec<SearchResult>;
    fn peek(&self, id: &str, start: usize, end: usize) -> String;
    fn diff(&self, a: &str, b: &str) -> String;
}
```

**Why this matters:** When the agent analyzes multiple files, each should get its own context so the LLM's limited attention isn't consumed by the raw content. The context stays out of chat history.

---

### 2. Evidence Tracking with Provenance

**What rlmagents does:**
Every search, peek, and exec is automatically recorded as `Evidence` with full provenance:

```python
@dataclass
class Evidence:
    source: str           # "search", "peek", "exec", "action"
    source_op: str        # "search_context", "exec_python", etc.
    context_id: str       # which context it came from
    file_path: str | None # if loaded from a file
    line_range: tuple | None
    pattern: str | None   # what was searched for
    snippet: str          # the actual evidence text
    command_exit_status: int | None
```

Evidence is surfaced via [get_evidence](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/middleware/_tools.py#1418-1450) and used in [finalize](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/middleware/_tools.py#1471-1500) to produce *cited conclusions*. You can also inspect via [evaluate_progress](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/middleware/_tools.py#1278-1317) which shows evidence summaries grouped by source.

**What rig-rlm lacks:**
No evidence tracking. Execution results go into chat history but aren't structured or queryable.

**Adoption plan:**
```rust
struct Evidence {
    source: String,         // "code_exec", "sub_agent", "search"
    context_id: Option<String>,
    snippet: String,
    line_range: Option<(usize, usize)>,
    pattern: Option<String>,
    exit_code: Option<i32>,
    timestamp: DateTime<Utc>,
}

// Add to AgentContext
evidence: Vec<Evidence>,

// In interpret_action, after ExecuteCode:
self.evidence.push(Evidence { ... });
```

**Why this matters:** When the agent produces a final answer, you want to know *what evidence it found and where*. This feeds directly into the GEPA evaluation metric — you could score based on evidence quality.

---

### 3. Auto-Load Large Results into Contexts

**What rlmagents does:**
The [RLMMiddleware](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/middleware/rlm.py#136-350) intercepts tool results. If any result exceeds `auto_load_threshold` (default 10K chars), it's autom atically loaded into an RLM context instead of being dumped into chat history. The agent sees a truncated preview + a pointer:

```
[Large result (42,500 chars) auto-loaded into RLM context 'auto_read_file'.
 Use search_context/peek_context to explore.]
```

**What rig-rlm lacks:**
Code execution results go directly into the conversation. Long outputs consume the context window and dilute attention.

**Adoption plan:**
In `interpret_action()` for `ExecuteCode`, after [sanitize_output()](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm/src/safety.rs#182-198):
```rust
if result.stdout.len() > AUTO_LOAD_THRESHOLD {
    let ctx_id = format!("auto_exec_{}", self.turn_count());
    self.context_manager.load(&ctx_id, &result.stdout);
    // Replace the feedback with a pointer
    let preview = &result.stdout[..600];
    format!("{preview}\n...[Full output ({} chars) in context '{}']",
            result.stdout.len(), ctx_id)
} else {
    result.stdout.clone()
}
```

---

## 🟡 Medium-Impact Ideas

### 4. Context Pressure & Auto-Compaction

**What rlmagents does:**
[RLMSessionManager](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/session_manager.py#113-547) tracks "context pressure" — how much work has been done in a context. When pressure exceeds thresholds (token count > 20K or iterations > 100), it automatically compacts:
1. Synthesizes a summary of work done so far
2. Prunes old evidence (keeps recent + evidence referenced in summary)
3. Replaces context content with the summary
4. Resets iteration counter

This prevents unbounded growth of REPL state during long analysis sessions.

**What rig-rlm lacks:**
The `max_turns` limit is the only guard. No automatic state compaction.

**Adoption plan:**
Add compaction to `AgentContext::run()`:
```rust
if self.turn_count() > 0 && self.turn_count() % COMPACTION_INTERVAL == 0 {
    self.compact_history(); // Summarize old turns, keep recent N
}
```

---

### 5. Recipe DSL (Declarative Multi-Step Pipelines)

**What rlmagents does:**
A declarative pipeline specification ([validate_recipe](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/recipes.py#71-162) → [estimate_recipe](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/recipes.py#164-184) → [run_recipe](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/middleware/_tools.py#1712-1743)) with operations like:

```json
{
  "version": "rlm.recipe.v1",
  "context_id": "analysis",
  "steps": [
    {"op": "load", "input": "file.txt"},
    {"op": "search", "pattern": "TODO"},
    {"op": "chunk", "chunk_size": 5000},
    {"op": "map_sub_query", "prompt": "Summarize this chunk"},
    {"op": "aggregate", "prompt": "Combine these summaries"},
    {"op": "finalize"}
  ],
  "budget": {"max_steps": 10, "max_sub_queries": 20}
}
```

This pre-validates the entire pipeline, estimates cost (sub-queries, steps), and then executes with budget constraints.

**Why this is interesting for rig-rlm:**
Your `ModulePipeline<A, B>` in [pipeline.rs](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm/src/pipeline.rs) already does two-stage composition. Recipes would extend this to N-stage declarative pipelines. Combined with GEPA optimization, you could optimize entire pipeline **sequences**, not just single instructions.

**Adoption plan:**
```rust
struct Recipe {
    steps: Vec<RecipeStep>,
    budget: Budget,
}

enum RecipeStep {
    Load { path: String },
    Search { pattern: String },
    Chunk { size: usize, overlap: usize },
    MapSubQuery { prompt: String },
    Aggregate { prompt: String },
    Finalize,
}

impl AgentContext {
    async fn run_recipe(&mut self, recipe: Recipe) -> Result<String>;
}
```

---

### 6. Conversation Summarization Middleware

**What rlmagents does:**
[SummarizationMiddleware](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/_harness/summarization.py#170-967) monitors conversation length. When it exceeds a trigger (token count or message count), it:
1. Partitions messages into "to summarize" and "to keep"
2. Persists the full history to backend storage (retrievable later)
3. Generates an LLM summary of the old messages
4. Replaces old messages with the summary
5. Also truncates large tool arguments in old messages ([TruncateArgsSettings](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/_harness/summarization.py#97-111))

**What rig-rlm lacks:**
History grows unboundedly. The `max_turns` limit just stops the agent rather than compacting.

**Adoption plan:**
Add a `summarize_history()` method to [AgentContext](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm/src/monad/context.rs#129-153):
```rust
async fn summarize_history(&mut self) -> Result<()> {
    if self.history.len() < TRIGGER_THRESHOLD { return Ok(()); }
    let to_summarize = &self.history.messages()[..cutoff];
    let summary = self.infer_summary(to_summarize).await?;
    self.history.replace_old_with_summary(summary, cutoff);
    Ok(())
}
```

---

### 7. Skills & Memory Middleware

**What rlmagents does:**
- **MemoryMiddleware**: Loads [AGENTS.md](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/AGENTS.md) files from configured paths and injects their content into the system prompt. This gives the agent persistent project knowledge.
- **SkillsMiddleware**: Discovers skill directories containing `SKILL.md` files (with YAML frontmatter), exposes a skill listing in the system prompt, and provides a `read_skill` tool for progressive disclosure (agent requests full skill content only when needed).

**What rig-rlm lacks:**
The system prompt is either hardcoded or loaded from `--instruction`. No mechanism for injecting project-specific or task-specific knowledge.

**Adoption plan:**
```rust
struct MemoryConfig {
    agents_md_paths: Vec<PathBuf>,
    skill_dirs: Vec<PathBuf>,
}

impl AgentContext {
    fn load_memory(&mut self) {
        for path in &self.config.memory.agents_md_paths {
            if let Ok(content) = std::fs::read_to_string(path) {
                self.system_prompt.push_str(&content);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

---

## 🟢 Nice-to-Have Ideas

### 8. Profile-Based Tool Filtering

**What rlmagents does:**
RLM tools are organized into profiles: `full` (24 tools), `reasoning` (21 tools), `core` (14 tools). You can also include/exclude individual tools. This prevents tool-overload for simpler agents.

**Relevance to rig-rlm:**
Your [Capabilities](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm/src/monad/capabilities.rs#22-36) struct already does action-level gating. But when you add more tools to the sandbox (SUBMIT, llm_query, etc.), having named profiles could be cleaner.

### 9. Cross-Context Search ([rg_search](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/middleware/_tools.py#1018-1098) Integration)

**What rlmagents does:**
[rg_search](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/middleware/_tools.py#1018-1098) tool wraps ripgrep for file-system-level code search, with an option to load results directly into an RLM context:
```python
rg_search(pattern="TODO", path="/repo", load_context_id="todos")
```

This bridges filesystem search with the context isolation system — search results go straight into an analysable context rather than polluting chat.

### 10. [think](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/middleware/_tools.py#1237-1258) and [evaluate_progress](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/middleware/_tools.py#1278-1317) Tools

**What rlmagents does:**
- [think](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/middleware/_tools.py#1237-1258): A structured scratchpad — the agent writes reasoning steps that are recorded but don't go to the LLM. Forces deliberate planning.
- [evaluate_progress](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/middleware/_tools.py#1278-1317): Agent self-assesses confidence and lists work remaining. Feeds into iteration control.

**Relevance to rig-rlm:**
You already have `AgentMonad::log()`. But a formal [think](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rlmagents/libs/rlmagents/rlmagents/middleware/_tools.py#1237-1258) action that records structured reasoning could improve transparency and feed into GEPA scoring.

---

## Recommended Integration Priority

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The items below are **new** relative to what's already in your [AGENTICA_IDEAS.md](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm/AGENTICA_IDEAS.md). That document already covers monadic loop improvements, provider abstraction, error handling, few-shot examples, and session persistence.

| # | Idea | Effort | Impact | Synergy with existing rig-rlm |
|---|------|--------|--------|-------------------------------|
| 1 | **Multi-Context Isolation** | Medium | 🔴 High | Builds on `Capture`/`Retrieve` variables |
| 2 | **Evidence Tracking** | Low | 🔴 High | Feeds into GEPA evaluation metrics |
| 3 | **Auto-Load Large Results** | Low | 🔴 High | Slot into existing [sanitize_output](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm/src/safety.rs#182-198) |
| 4 | **Context Auto-Compaction** | Medium | 🟡 Medium | Extends beyond `max_turns` hard limit |
| 5 | **Recipe DSL** | High | 🟡 Medium | Extends `ModulePipeline<A,B>` to N stages |
| 6 | **Conversation Summarization** | Medium | 🟡 Medium | Needs LLM call; extends history management |
| 7 | **Skills/Memory Loading** | Low | 🟡 Medium | System prompt injection, filesystem |
| 8 | **Tool Profiles** | Low | 🟢 Nice | Extends [Capabilities](file:///home/sumit-mittal/dev-stuff/rig-rlm/src/monad/capabilities.rs#22-36) |
| 9 | **rg_search → Context** | Low | 🟢 Nice | Filesystem + context bridge |
| 10 | **think/evaluate_progress** | Low | 🟢 Nice | Extends logging/capture system |

**Suggested order:** Items 2 → 3 → 1 → 7 → 4 → 6 → 5 → rest

Start with **evidence tracking** (low effort, high value, directly improves GEPA scoring), then **auto-load** (trivial addition to `interpret_action`), then **multi-context isolation** (the biggest architectural win but requires more work).
